___________________________________________________________________

📘 FUNCTIONS SIMILAR TO map() AND filter()
___________________________________________________________________

🔹 1️⃣ map()
    Used to transform every element in a dataset.
-------------------------------------------------------------------
syntax:
        map(function, iterable)
-------------------------------------------------------------------
Example:
        sales = [100, 200, 300]
        tax = list(map(lambda x: x * 1.18, sales))
        print(tax)
Output
        [118.0, 236.0, 354.0]
___________________________________________________________________

🔹 2️⃣ filter()
    Used to select elements based on a condition.
-------------------------------------------------------------------
syntax:
        filter(function, iterable)
-------------------------------------------------------------------
Example:
        sales = [500, 1200, 700, 1800]
        high_sales = list(filter(lambda x: x > 1000, sales))
        print(high_sales)
Output
        [1200, 1800]

✔ keeps values that satisfy condition
___________________________________________________________________

🔹 3️⃣ zip()
        Used to combine multiple datasets together.
-------------------------------------------------------------------
syntax:
        zip(list1, list2)
-------------------------------------------------------------------
Example:
        products = ["apple", "mango", "banana"]
        sales = [100, 200, 150]
        data = list(zip(products, sales))
        print(data)
Output
        [('apple', 100), ('mango', 200), ('banana', 150)]
-------------------------------------------------------------------
✔ used for pairing datasets
Very common in analytics.
___________________________________________________________________

🔹 4️⃣ enumerate()
    Used when you need index + value together.
-------------------------------------------------------------------
syntax:
        enumerate(iterable)
-------------------------------------------------------------------
Example:
        sales = [100, 200, 300]
        for index, value in enumerate(sales):
            print(index, value)
Output
        0 100
        1 200
        2 300
-------------------------------------------------------------------
✔ useful when tracking row numbers.
___________________________________________________________________

🔹 5️⃣ any()
    Returns True if ANY condition is true.
-------------------------------------------------------------------
syntax:
        any(iterable)
-------------------------------------------------------------------
syntax:
        any(condition for item in iterable)        
-------------------------------------------------------------------
Example:
        sales = [200, 300, 1500]
        print(any(x > 1000 for x in sales))
Output
        True
-------------------------------------------------------------------
✔ checks if at least one value satisfies condition
___________________________________________________________________

🔹 6️⃣ all()
    Returns True only if ALL conditions are true.
-------------------------------------------------------------------
syntax:
        all(iterable)
-------------------------------------------------------------------
syntax:
        all(condition for item in iterable)        
-------------------------------------------------------------------
Example:
        sales = [200, 300, 400]
        print(all(x > 100 for x in sales))
Output
        True
-------------------------------------------------------------------
✔ checks if every value satisfies condition
___________________________________________________________________

🔹 7️⃣ sorted()
    Sorts data.
    sorted() is used to sort elements in ascending or descending order.
    It does not modify the original list.
    It returns a new sorted list.
-------------------------------------------------------------------
syntax:
        sorted(iterable)
-------------------------------------------------------------------
Example:
        sales = [500, 200, 900]
        print(sorted(sales))
Output:
        [200, 500, 900]
-------------------------------------------------------------------
✔ sorting datasets
___________________________________________________________________

🧠 MEMORY TRICK

Think of them like data pipeline tools:

map()        → modify data
filter()     → select data
zip()        → combine data
enumerate()  → index + value
any()        → check at least one
all()        → check everything
sorted()     → order data

🔥 Most Important for Data Analytics
___________________________________________________________________

Focus mainly on:

    + map()
    + filter()
    + zip()
    + enumerate()
    + sorted()

These appear everywhere in Python data workflows.
___________________________________________________________________
